'''Kieran Tierney''' (born 5 June 1997) is a Scottish professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[left-back]] for [[Scottish Premiership]] club [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]].

Tierney came through the [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] youth system and made his first-team debut in April 2015. After playing 170 games for the club, he joined [[Premier League]] side [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in August 2019 for a fee reported at £25&nbsp;million. After six years with Arsenal, including one on loan with [[La Liga]] club [[Real Sociedad]], Tierney returned to Celtic in June 2025. He made his Scotland international debut in March 2016, and has since made more than 50 appearances for the senior side.

==Club career==
===Early life and youth football===
Kieran Tierney<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/1335777 |title=2019/20 Premier League squads confirmed |publisher=Premier League |date=3 September 2019 |access-date=3 September 2019 |archive-date=3 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190903201046/https://www.premierleague.com/news/1335777 |url-status=live }}</ref> was born on 5 June 1997<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/12185/Kieran-Tierney/overview |title=Kieran Tierney: Overview |publisher=Premier League |access-date=17 August 2019 |archive-date=17 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817170338/https://www.premierleague.com/players/12185/Kieran-Tierney/overview |url-status=live }}</ref> in [[Douglas, Isle of Man|Douglas]] on the [[Isle of Man]],<ref name="iom">{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/13899935.Kieran_Tierney_taking_his_Manx_connections_seriously_as_he_embarks_on_Celtic_career/|title=Kieran Tierney taking his Manx connections seriously as he embarks on Celtic career|last=Fisher|first=Stewart|date=27 October 2015|work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|publisher=[[Newsquest]]|access-date=2 May 2017|archive-date=20 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420141805/http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/13899935.Kieran_Tierney_taking_his_Manx_connections_seriously_as_he_embarks_on_Celtic_career/|url-status=live}}</ref> and moved to [[Wishaw]] in Scotland aged 10 months.<ref name=gemmell>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/local-news/wishaws-kieran-tierney-pays-tribute-10030469|title=Wishaw's Kieran Tierney pays tribute to Celtic legend Tommy Gemmell|last=Temlett|first=Michael|date=18 March 2017|work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|access-date=2 May 2017|archive-date=19 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419044859/http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/local-news/wishaws-kieran-tierney-pays-tribute-10030469|url-status=live}}</ref> He supported [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] as a child and signed for the club when he was seven years old. He was educated at [[Motherwell]] schools St Brendan's RC Primary and [[Our Lady's High School, Motherwell|Our Lady's High]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tes.com/magazine/archived/scotland-players-old-schools-send-good-luck-messages|title=Scotland players' old schools send good luck messages|last=Hepburn|first=Henry|date=11 June 2021|work=[[TES (magazine)|TES]]}}</ref> (one year group behind fellow footballers, twins [[Nicky Cadden|Nicky]] and [[Chris Cadden]])<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/celtic/chris-cadden-hopes-to-beat-old-school-pal-kieran-tierney-1-4619798 |title=Chris Cadden hopes to beat old school pal Kieran Tierney |work=[[The Scotsman]] |date=22 November 2017 |access-date=30 May 2018 |archive-date=23 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171123102502/https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/celtic/chris-cadden-hopes-to-beat-old-school-pal-kieran-tierney-1-4619798 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/11/21/cadden-clan-descend-hampden-park-chris-aims-upset-celtic/ |title=Cadden clan descend on Hampden Park as Chris aims to upset Celtic |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=21 November 2017 |access-date=30 May 2018 |archive-date=22 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171122004831/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/11/21/cadden-clan-descend-hampden-park-chris-aims-upset-celtic/ |url-status=live }}</ref> then attended [[St Ninian's High School, Kirkintilloch]], which has a development partnership with Celtic. He has spoken of his hope of emulating the late [[Tommy Gemmell]], a member of the [[Lisbon Lions]] team who also grew up in Wishaw (specifically, [[Craigneuk]]) and played in the same position.<ref name=gemmell/>

Tierney progressed through the various youth ranks and earned a reputation as a dependable wide player in the club's [[Celtic F.C. Reserve and Youth squads|development squad]], both in defence and attack.<ref name="debut">{{cite web|last=McKay|first=Kenny|title=Kieran Tierney determined to make further progress at the club|url=http://www.celticfc.net/news/6395|website=Celtic FC|access-date=2 August 2015|date=6 August 2014|archive-date=6 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140806225108/http://www.celticfc.net/news/6395|url-status=dead}}</ref> He travelled with the first-team squad on a pre-season trip to Finland in August 2014, and made his debut in a friendly against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] there. Although Celtic lost, Tierney described his first appearance for the first team as a "dream come true".<ref name="debut" /> He continued to play in the development squad throughout 2014–15, and in October 2014 during a [[SPFL Development League|Development League]] match against [[Heart of Midlothian F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Heart of Midlothian]] he scored a goal from the edge of his own penalty box.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McKay|first1=Kenny|title=Kieran Tierney wonder goal secures Celtic win|url=http://www.celticfc.net/news/6964|website=Celtic FC|access-date=2 August 2015|date=28 October 2014|archive-date=23 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923221701/http://www.celticfc.net/news/6964|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Kyle|first1=Gregor|title=Video: Celtic kid Kieran Tierney scores from edge of his own penalty box|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/video-celtic-kid-kieran-tierney-4533534|website=Daily Record|access-date=2 August 2015|date=30 October 2014|archive-date=30 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030200258/http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/video-celtic-kid-kieran-tierney-4533534|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Celtic===
====2015–16: Debut and breakthrough====
Tierney made his competitive senior debut for Celtic on 22 April 2015, coming on as an 81st-minute substitute in a [[Scottish Premiership]] match against [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2015/04/22/scotland/premier-league/dundee-fc/celtic-fc/1704591/|title=Dundee vs. Celtic|publisher=Soccerway|access-date=23 April 2015|archive-date=20 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150320033542/https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2015/04/22/scotland/premier-league/dundee-fc/celtic-fc/1704591/|url-status=live}}</ref> He made one further first-team appearance that season, playing over an hour in a league match away at [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Games Involving Tierney, Kieran in Season 2014/2015|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/celtic/player_games.php?playerid=6774&page=2|website=FitbaStats|access-date=2 August 2015|archive-date=24 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924043302/http://www.fitbastats.com/celtic/player_games.php?playerid=6774&page=2|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Tierney enjoyed a breakthrough season in [[2015–16 in Scottish football|2015–16]], appearing in over 30 matches and displacing the more experienced [[Emilio Izaguirre]] as first-choice [[left back]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/14314216.Tierney__I_took_Emilio_s_Celtic_place_but_he_still_helps_me_every_day/|title=Kieran Tierney: I took Emilio Izaguirre's Celtic place but he still helps me every day|last=Macpherson|first=Graeme|date=2 March 2016|work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|publisher=[[Newsquest]]|access-date=17 October 2016|archive-date=18 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018224621/http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/14314216.Tierney__I_took_Emilio_s_Celtic_place_but_he_still_helps_me_every_day/|url-status=live}}</ref> For his performances he was awarded with both the [[PFA Scotland Young Player of the Year|Players']] and [[SFWA Young Player of the Year|Writers']] Young Player annual awards,<ref name = "players 2016"/><ref name = "writers 2016"/> while Celtic also won the league title. Despite interest from [[Premier League]] clubs, Tierney signed a new five-year contract on 24 June 2016, keeping him at Parkhead until 2021.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36620462|title=Celtic: Kieran Tierney signs five-year contract extension|last=Barnes|first=John|date=24 June 2016|work=BBC Sport|access-date=10 March 2017|archive-date=7 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407031134/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36620462|url-status=live}}</ref> After making his first appearances in the [[2016–17 UEFA Champions League group stage#Group C|group stage]] of the [[UEFA Champions League]], Tierney suffered ankle ligament damage during training on 27 October 2016 and was initially ruled out of action for two months.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37797772|title=Kieran Tierney: Celtic and Scotland defender ruled out for two months|date=29 October 2016|work=BBC Sport|access-date=30 October 2016|archive-date=31 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031222705/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37797772|url-status=live}}</ref> During the layoff, which caused him to miss the [[2016 Scottish League Cup final (November)|League Cup final]], he received treatment on a recurring shoulder injury and attended several Celtic matches as a typical supporter in the company of his childhood friends.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/scottish/celtic/injured-tierney-savoured-roaring-on-celts-in-stands-35422285.html|title=Injured Tierney savoured roaring on Celts in stands|date=4 February 2017|work=The Belfast Telegraph|access-date=8 November 2017|archive-date=9 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109023324/https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/scottish/celtic/injured-tierney-savoured-roaring-on-celts-in-stands-35422285.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

====2017–2019: Back-to-back domestic trebles====
[[File:FC Salzburg versus Celtic FC (4. Oktober 2918 Gruppe B, Zweiter Spieltag) 15.jpg|thumb|right|Tierney alongside [[Alexander Walke]], Celtc v. [[FC Salzburg]], 2018]] 
On 22 January 2017, after missing three months, he made his long-awaited return to the Celtic team in a [[Scottish Cup]] tie against [[Albion Rovers F.C.|Albion Rovers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38626880|title=Albion Rovers 0–3 Celtic|last=Wilson|first=Richard|date=22 January 2017|work=BBC Sport|access-date=8 May 2017|archive-date=20 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220223739/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38626880|url-status=live}}</ref> Tierney was crowned PFA Scotland Young Player of the Year for the second consecutive season on 7 May, making him the first to achieve this since [[Craig Levein]] in 1986.<ref name = "pfa 2017">{{cite news|url=https://stv.tv/sport/football/1387806-celtic-seal-a-treble-of-awards-at-pfa-scotland-ceremony/|title=Celtic seal a treble of awards at PFA Scotland ceremony|last=Brannan|first=Laura|date=7 May 2017|publisher=[[stv.tv]]|access-date=8 May 2017|archive-date=29 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929000735/https://stv.tv/sport/football/1387806-celtic-seal-a-treble-of-awards-at-pfa-scotland-ceremony/|url-status=live}}</ref> He suffered a jaw injury early in the [[2017 Scottish Cup final|Scottish Cup final]] and had to be substituted for treatment.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/05/27/celtic-2-aberdeen-1tom-rogic-shatters-dons-secure-historic-clean/ | title=Celtic 2 Aberdeen 1: Tom Rogic shatters Dons to secure historic clean sweep with Scottish Cup final win | work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=27 May 2017 | access-date=30 May 2017 | archive-date=28 May 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170528071539/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/05/27/celtic-2-aberdeen-1tom-rogic-shatters-dons-secure-historic-clean/ | url-status=live }}</ref> Celtic won the match 2–1 to complete a [[Treble (association football)#Domestic trebles|domestic treble]] and [[List of unbeaten football club seasons|undefeated season]]. In spite of his lengthy injury absence, he featured in 40 matches during the campaign.

On 8 August 2017, Tierney was named as [[Captain (association football)|captain]] while also moving to [[Defender (association football)#Central defender|central defender]] to command a back line of teenagers in a [[2017–18 Scottish League Cup#Second round|Scottish League Cup]] fixture against [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]]; Celtic won the game 5–0, with Tierney providing an [[Assist (football)|assist]] and scoring with a "wonderful strike" from 40 yards.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40829930 |title=Celtic 5–0 Kilmarnock |work=BBC Sport |date=8 August 2017 |access-date=8 August 2017 |archive-date=5 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905050605/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40829930 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 30 October, a week after scoring in an important [[2017–18 Scottish Premiership|league]] victory away to closest challengers [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]], he extended his contract with Celtic until 2023.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41810466|title=Kieran Tierney: Celtic left-back signs new six-year contract|date=22 February 2017|work=BBC Sport|access-date=8 November 2017|archive-date=7 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107143845/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41810466|url-status=live}}</ref>

By the end of the season, he had collected further personal accolades—winning both the [[PFA Scotland Young Player of the Year|Players']] and [[SFWA Young Player of the Year|Writers']] Young Player awards for the third campaign in succession—and performed a major role in securing a historic 'double treble' for the club, making more than 50 appearances and playing the entirety of the domestic cup finals, both being 2–0 wins over [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]].<ref name=lc1718/><ref name=sc1718/> Tierney played in Celtic's victory over Aberdeen in the [[2018 Scottish League Cup Final]] on 2 December 2018.<ref name=lc1819/> Soon afterwards a hip injury meant that he was ruled out of action, returning on 24 February 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic star Kieran Tierney blasts Motherwell over lack of respect after sneaky throw-in goal|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/celtic-star-kieran-tierney-blasts-14048209|work=Daily Record|date=24 February 2019|access-date=25 February 2019|archive-date=25 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190225045215/https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/celtic-star-kieran-tierney-blasts-14048209|url-status=live}}</ref> He then suffered from a hernia, which subsequently required surgery.<ref name="hernia">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48731196|title=Kieran Tierney: Arsenal 'optimistic' over Celtic defender deal|last=Ornstein|first=David|date=22 June 2019|work=BBC Sport|access-date=22 June 2019|archive-date=22 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622170507/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48731196|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Arsenal===
====2019–2023: FA Cup win and injuries====
On 8 August 2019, Tierney signed for [[Premier League]] club [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], for a reported £25&nbsp;million fee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/kieran-tierney-joins-long-term-deal|title=Kieran Tierney joins on long-term deal|publisher=Arsenal F.C.|access-date=8 August 2019|archive-date=8 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808155104/https://www.arsenal.com/news/kieran-tierney-joins-long-term-deal|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49283667 |title=Kieran Tierney: Celtic defender completes £25m Arsenal move |website=BBC Sport |date=8 August 2019 |access-date=8 August 2019 |archive-date=8 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808170510/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49283667 |url-status=live }}</ref> Tierney missed the early part of the 2019–20 season, having undergone a double hernia operation in May 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49780536 |title=Kieran Tierney: Scotland defender makes injury comeback for Arsenal U23 |website=BBC Sport |date=21 September 2019 |access-date=21 September 2019 |archive-date=21 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921090511/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49780536 |url-status=live }}</ref> He made his first-team debut for Arsenal in a 5–0 win against [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] in the [[EFL Cup]] on 24 September.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49823156 |title=Kieran Tierney: Scotland full-back enjoys impressive Arsenal debut |website=BBC Sport |date=25 September 2019 |access-date=25 September 2019 |archive-date=25 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925093458/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49823156 |url-status=live }}</ref> Tierney assisted the first goal in a 4–0 home win against [[Standard Liège]] scored by [[Gabriel Martinelli]] a week later.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49874359 |title=Arsenal 4–0 Standard Liege |website=BBC Sport |date=3 October 2019 |access-date=8 October 2019 |archive-date=3 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191003043401/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49874359 |url-status=live }}</ref> He made his first appearance in the Premier League on 27 October, in a 2–2 draw with [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]. His season was further disrupted after suffering a dislocated shoulder in the game against West Ham United.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50113576|title=Arsenal 2–2 Crystal Palace: Gunners surrender two-goal advantage as Granit Xhaka booed off|work=BBC Sport |date=27 October 2019|access-date=28 October 2019|archive-date=26 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026012508/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50113576|url-status=live}}</ref>

Tierney's impressive performances for Arsenal following the resumption of the Premier League after the [[COVID-19 pandemic]] saw him receive Arsenal's Player of the Month award for June.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/tierney-our-june-player-month|title=Tierney is our June Player of the Month!|publisher=Arsenal F.C.|access-date=13 July 2020|archive-date=13 July 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200713150320/https://www.arsenal.com/news/tierney-our-june-player-month|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Arsenal on 26 July, in a 3–2 win against [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] on the final day of the 2019–20 Premier League season.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/kieran-tierney-mark-arsenal-former-22419340 |title=Kieran Tierney off the mark for Arsenal as former Celtic star scores first Premier League goal |first=Steven |last=Mair |newspaper=Daily Record |date=26 July 2020 |access-date=26 July 2020 |archive-date=26 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200726161927/https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/kieran-tierney-mark-arsenal-former-22419340 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 1 August 2020, Tierney was selected to start in the [[2020 FA Cup final|FA Cup final]] against Chelsea, as Arsenal won their 14th FA Cup.<ref name="bbc">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53546100 |title=Arsenal 2–1 Chelsea |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=1 August 2020 |access-date=2 August 2020 |archive-date=1 August 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200801202716/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53546100 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 28 August 2020, Tierney was in the starting 11 in the [[2020 FA Community Shield]], which Arsenal clinched a 5–4 victory over [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the penalty shootout after the match was 1–1 after 90 minutes.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Arsenal 1–1 Liverpool (5–4 on pens): Pierre-Emerick Aubameyang secures Community Shield shootout win|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12059158/arsenal-1-1-liverpool-5-4-on-pens-pierre-emerick-aubameyang-secures-community-shield-shootout-win|access-date=26 February 2021|website=Sky Sports|language=en}}</ref> On 2 January 2021, Tierney scored the opening goal in a 4–0 away league win over [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and later assisted the final goal, scored by [[Alexandre Lacazette]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/55450393 |title=West Brom 0–4 Arsenal: Arsenal see off Baggies in ruthless display |work=BBC Sport |date=2 January 2021|access-date=16 January 2021}}</ref> His stunning strike was subsequently voted the January Goal of the Month on the Arsenal official website.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Kieran Tierney tops January Goal of the Month poll|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/kieran-tierney-tops-january-goal-month-poll|access-date=15 February 2021|publisher=Arsenal F.C.|language=en}}</ref> On 25 February, he scored a goal in a 3–2 win over [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] in the [[2020–21 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] round of 32, making him the first Scotsman to score for Arsenal in a European competition since [[Willie Young (footballer, born 1951)|Willie Young]] in March 1980.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/56185885 |title=Arsenal 3–2 Benfica |website=BBC Sport |date=25 February 2021 }}</ref> In June 2021, he signed a long-term contract with Arsenal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11670/12341803/kieran-tierney-feels-amazing-after-signing-long-term-arsenal-contract-extension |title=Kieran Tierney 'feels amazing' after signing long-term Arsenal contract extension |website=Sky Sports |date=25 June 2021 }}</ref>

Tierney played regularly for Arsenal during the 2021–22 season until suffering a season-ending knee injury in March.<ref name = march22injury>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.com/sport/football/article/all-or-nothing-documentary-reveals-freak-cause-of-knee-injury-that-blighted-kieran-tierneys-arsenal-season-vt0bmb8kc |title=All or Nothing documentary reveals freak cause of knee injury that blighted Kieran Tierney's Arsenal season |newspaper=[[The Times]] |first=Gary |last=Jacob |date=17 August 2022 |access-date=17 August 2022 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> Arsenal lost league games against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]], [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton]], [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]] and [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle]] following his injury, and they narrowly missed out on Champions League qualification.<ref name = march22injury/> It was later revealed in the ''[[All or Nothing: Arsenal]]'' series that Tierney had hyper-extended the knee during a game in February, but aggravated it a month later while walking in the Arsenal training ground.<ref name = march22injury/> He returned to action at the start of the 2022–23 season.<ref name = march22injury/>

Arsenal signed [[Oleksandr Zinchenko (footballer)|Oleksandr Zinchenko]] from Manchester City during the summer of 2022, and during the 2022–23 season the Ukrainian played most Premier League minutes at left back ahead of Tierney.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/arsenal-battle-kieran-tierney-unlikely-29226295 |title=The Arsenal battle Kieran Tierney is unlikely to win as Oleksandr Zinchenko stat comparison shows why Arteta prefers him |newspaper=Daily Record |first=Will |last=Lancaster |date=15 February 2023 |accessdate=2 February 2023}}</ref> This led to speculation that Tierney would look to leave Arsenal during the summer of 2023.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/sport/23353174.arsenals-mikel-arteta-quizzed-kieran-tierney-newcastle-transfer/ |title=Arsenal's Mikel Arteta quizzed on Kieran Tierney Newcastle transfer |newspaper=The Northern Echo |first=Dominic |last=Shaw |date=28 February 2023 |accessdate=2 March 2023}}</ref>

====2023–2024: Loan to Real Sociedad====
On 27 August 2023, Tierney joined [[La Liga]] club [[Real Sociedad]] on a season-long [[Loan (association football)|loan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.realsociedad.eus/en/news/details/path-to-the-stars|title=Path to the stars|publisher=Real Sociedad|date=27 August 2023|access-date=27 August 2023}}</ref> He made his full debut in a 5–3 win over [[Granada CF|Granada]], for which he was labelled 'exquisite' by Real Sociedad boss [[Imanol Alguacil]].<ref>{{cite news |date=3 September 2023 |last=Walker |first=Mark |title='Exquisite' – Kieran Tierney handed rave review after stunning Real Sociedad debut |url=https://www.thenational.scot/sport/23764128.kieran-tierney-labelled-exquisite-real-sociedad-debut/ |access-date=18 September 2023 |website=The National |language=en |url-access=subscription}}</ref> He followed this up with an impressive performance against [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] on 17 September.<ref>{{cite news |last=Galindo |first=Alan |date=18 September 2023 |title=Kieran Tierney 'sparks' Real Sociedad goal at Real Madrid in number of key moments |url=https://www.glasgowlive.co.uk/sport/kieran-tierney-sparks-real-sociedad-27734339 |access-date=18 September 2023 |website=GlasgowLive |language=en}}</ref> His season was interrupted by two hamstring injuries, sustained in September and January.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2024/feb/14/kieran-tierney-i-was-up-against-mbappe-it-helps-you-in-the-long-run |title=Kieran Tierney: 'I was up against Mbappé … it helps you in the long run' |newspaper=The Guardian |date=14 February 2024 |accessdate=15 February 2024 |first=Sid |last=Lowe}}</ref>

====Return from loan====
Tierney returned to Arsenal over the summer after picking up a hamstring injury at [[UEFA Euro 2024|Euro 2024]]. He made his long-awaited return to training on 21 November 2024.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/kieran-tierney-arsenal-fc-injury-update-training-b1195526.html|title=Forgotten Arsenal star confirms training return after injury nightmare|first=Matt|last=Verri|date=21 November 2024|website=The Standard}}</ref> On 20 April 2025, he made his 100th [[Premier League]] appearance for the club, in a 4–0 win over [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] at [[Portman Road]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribuna.com/amp/en/news/2025-04-20-kieran-tierney-made-his-100th-premier-league-appearance-for-arsenal/|title=Kieran Tierney made his 100th Premier League appearance for Arsenal|website=tribuna.com |date=20 April 2025 }}</ref> On 25 May 2025, Tierney opened the scoring in a 2–1 win away to [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] in his final game for the club, having made a total of 144 appearances in all competitions, scoring 6 goals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/may/25/southampton-arsenal-premier-league-match-report|title=Ødegaard strikes late to earn Arsenal win at Southampton after Tierney's farewell goal|first=Ed|last=Aarons|date=25 May 2025|work=The Guardian}}</ref>

=== Return to Celtic ===
Tierney's former club, [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], confirmed in February 2025 that they had reached a pre-contract agreement for him to return to the club on a permanent basis in the summer of that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/13306877/celtic-transfer-kieran-tierney-signs-pre-contract-agreement-to-leave-arsenal-and-re-join-the-hoops-this-summer|title=Celtic transfer: Kieran Tierney signs pre-contract agreement to leave Arsenal and re-join the Hoops this summer|website=Sky Sports}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/articles/c15z988kpw2o.amp|title=Kieran Tierney: What player are Celtic getting six years after his exit?|date=11 February 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> His departure from Arsenal was announced in June 2025,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/contract-updates-20-players-depart-summer |title=Contract updates: 20 players to depart this summer |date=4 June 2025 |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |access-date=4 June 2025}}</ref> and he signed a five-year contract with Celtic later that month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/clyzm439d28o |title=Kieran Tierney: Celtic defender agrees five-year deal on return from Arsenal|date=10 June 2025|accessdate=10 June 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 3 August, he made his second debut for the club in a 1–0 win against [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] in the league.<ref>{{cite web |title=Celtic began their Scottish Premiership season with a victory, but were far from convincing as they struggled to break down a resilient St Mirren |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c3dpe12k9z8t#Report |website=bbc.com |access-date=9 August 2025}}</ref> He scored the first goal of his second spell on 9 November; the second in Celtic's 4–0 win against [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Celtic ease past Kilmarnock to narrow gap at summit|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c9wvxxpddxwt|first=George|last=O'Neill|website=BBC Sport|date=9 November 2025|access-date=16 March 2026}}</ref>  On 1 March 2026, Tierney scored Celtic's first goal against their [[Old Firm|arch rivals]] [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], as the ''Hoops'' came from 2–0 down to draw 2–2 in the Scottish Premiership game at [[Ibrox Stadium|Ibrox]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cr5lrgp4g18t|title=Celtic rescue dramatic draw at Rangers as both spill points in Hearts chase|first=Kheredine|last=Idessane|date=1 March 2026|access-date=1 March 2026|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

==International career==
Tierney played for Scotland at [[Scotland national football team|Scotland U18]] and [[Scotland national football team|Scotland U19]] levels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/football_player_profile.cfm?page=1848&playerID=141507&squadID=9|title=Kieran Tierney|work=scottishfa.co.uk|publisher=Scottish Football Association|access-date=3 October 2015|archive-date=4 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004012558/http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/football_player_profile.cfm?page=1848&playerID=141507&squadID=9|url-status=live}}</ref> He had also considered playing for the [[Ellan Vannin football team|Ellan Vannin team]] that represents the Isle of Man when the [[ConIFA]] World Cup competition was being held.<ref name="iom"/> Tierney received his first call-up to the senior [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] squad on 10 March 2016 for a friendly against [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35770855|title=Scotland: Six new call-ups for Czech Republic and Denmark friendlies|date=10 March 2016|work=BBC Sport|access-date=10 March 2016|archive-date=10 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310175550/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35770855|url-status=live}}</ref> Tierney played for the first half of the match on 30 March, which Scotland won 1–0 at [[Hampden Park]]; he was replaced at the break by his Celtic teammate [[Charlie Mulgrew]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35923550 |title=Scotland 1–0 Denmark: McGinn and Tierney shine on debuts |first=Alasdair |last=Lamont |work=BBC Sport |date=30 March 2016 |access-date=6 April 2016 |archive-date=5 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405045401/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35923550 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Due to his greater versatility compared to fellow left-back [[Andy Robertson]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45459420 |title=Andy Robertson & Kieran Tierney both must play – Gordon Strachan |work=BBC Sport |date=8 September 2018 |access-date=8 September 2018 |archive-date=9 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909144947/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45459420 |url-status=live }}</ref> Tierney was deployed at [[right back]] in Scotland's matches against [[Slovenia national football team|Slovenia]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39302192 |title=Scotland 1–0 Slovenia |work=BBC Sport |date=26 March 2017 |access-date=9 August 2017 |archive-date=14 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191114095953/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39302192 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]] and [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]], and on the left of a three-man defence in the fixture at home to [[England national football team|England]] during [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification&nbsp;– UEFA Group F|World Cup qualifiers]] in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2017/jun/11/scotland-england-five-talking-points-tierney-strachan-sterling-oxlade-chamberlain |title=Scotland 2–2 England |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=11 June 2017 |access-date=9 August 2017 |archive-date=9 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809041705/https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2017/jun/11/scotland-england-five-talking-points-tierney-strachan-sterling-oxlade-chamberlain |url-status=live }}</ref> Tierney was selected as Scotland captain for a friendly match against [[Netherlands national football team|the Netherlands]] in November 2017, where he played as a central defender in a 1–0 defeat.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41840573 |title=Scotland 0–1 Netherlands |work=BBC Sport |date=9 November 2017 |access-date=10 November 2017 |archive-date=9 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109234209/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41840573 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In October 2018, Tierney scored a decisive [[own goal]] in a 2–1 loss to [[Israel national football team|Israel]] in a [[UEFA Nations League]] fixture.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/sport/16977913.israel-2-scotland-1-kieran-tierney-own-goal-caps-a-miserable-night-for-alex-mcleishs-men-in-haifa/ |title=Israel 2 Scotland 1: Kieran Tierney own goal caps a miserable night for Alex McLeish's men in Haifa |work=[[Evening Times]] |author=Matthew Lindsay |date=11 October 2018 |access-date=12 October 2018 |archive-date=12 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012214541/https://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/sport/16977913.israel-2-scotland-1-kieran-tierney-own-goal-caps-a-miserable-night-for-alex-mcleishs-men-in-haifa/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> Speaking after the game, Robertson said that both he and Tierney were being played out of position in the 3–5–2 system adopted by [[Alex McLeish]] to accommodate both players.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45832123 |title=Andy Robertson: Kieran Tierney and I are 'both out of position' |work=BBC Sport |date=12 October 2018 |access-date=13 October 2018 |archive-date=12 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012212012/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45832123 |url-status=live }}</ref> In November 2019, Tierney withdrew from the Scotland squad ahead of their [[UEFA Euro 2020]] qualifiers against Cyprus and Kazakhstan due to a hip injury.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/scotland/50389854|title=Scotland: Andy Robertson, Ryan Fraser and Scott McTominay 'genuinely injured' – Alex Dyer|date=12 November 2019|work=BBC Sport|access-date=12 November 2019|archive-date=12 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112104223/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/scotland/50389854|url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2020, he was required to pull out of the squad for a Euro 2020 play-off semi-final against Israel after being in close contact with [[Stuart Armstrong]], who had tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54453593|title=Scotland trio out after positive test|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> It was later confirmed by Armstrong, Tierney and [[Ryan Christie]] that they had been playing video games in the same room.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Winton |first1=Richard |title=Euro 2020: How Call of Duty might have ended Scotland's dream |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57370130 |access-date=8 June 2021 |work=BBC Sport |date=6 June 2021}}</ref>

Tierney provided three assists in a 4–0 win against the [[Faroe Islands national football team|Faroe Islands]] on 31 March 2021, despite playing from a central defensive position.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/56598023 |title=Kieran Tierney: Arsenal defender provides three assists in Scotland romp |website=BBC Sport |date=31 March 2021 |accessdate=1 April 2021}}</ref> He then played in two of Scotland's matches at the delayed [[UEFA Euro 2020]] finals in June 2021, as he missed the opening match with [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]] due to injury.{{citation needed|date=October 2023}} Tierney scored his first goal for Scotland on 24 March 2022, in a friendly against [[Poland national football team|Poland]] at Hampden.<ref>{{Cite news |date=24 March 2022 |title=International friendly: Controversial late penalty denies Scotland win over Poland – reaction |language=en-GB |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/live/football/60807549 |access-date=24 March 2022}}</ref> Soon afterwards he suffered a training ground injury that kept him out of action for the rest of the 2021–22 season.<ref name = march22injury/> This caused him to miss a World Cup playoff against [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]] in June, which Scotland lost 3–1.{{citation needed|date=October 2023}} Tierney appeared five times for Scotland during their successful [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying]] campaign, with the team winning all five of the matches he played and conceding only one goal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/tierney-gets-scotland-selection-euro-2024?page=3|title=Tierney gets Scotland selection for Euro 2024|date=15 June 2024|access-date=15 June 2024|publisher=Arsenal F.C.}}</ref>

On 7 June 2024, Tierney was named in Scotland's squad for the [[UEFA Euro 2024]] finals in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/record-breaking-goalkeeper-gordon-out-scotland-euro-2024-squad-2024-06-07/|title=Record-breaking goalkeeper Gordon out of Scotland's Euro 2024 squad|date=7 June 2024|access-date=15 June 2024|website=Reuters}}</ref> A week later, he started the opening match of the tournament, playing 76 minutes before being substituted for [[Scott McKenna]], as Scotland lost 5–1 to hosts [[Germany national football team|Germany]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c844x4y3ee3t|title=Ruthless Germany humble 10-man Scotland in Euro 2024 opener|website=BBC Sport|access-date=15 June 2024}}</ref> Tierney was substituted with an injury in the 61st minute of the second group match against [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] on 19 June. This injury made him unavailable for the final match against [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]], which they lost 1–0 to finish bottom of [[UEFA Euro 2024 Group A|Group A]] with one point from three matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028e-1b2c127c5b92-e020507872a2-1000--scotland-1-1-switzerland-clarke-s-men-keep-group-a-hopes-/|title=Scotland 1–1 Switzerland: Clarke's men keep Group A hopes alive|access-date=24 June 2024|publisher=UEFA}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/match/2036186--scotland-vs-hungary/lineups/|title=Scotland vs Hungary: Line-ups|access-date=24 June 2024|publisher=UEFA}}</ref> Tierney gained his [[Scotland Men's International Roll of Honour|50th cap]] in a 3–1 defeat to [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]] on 6 June 2025.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whtimes.co.uk/sport/national/25221940.scotland-goalkeeper-cieran-slicker-debut-forget-home-defeat-iceland/|title=Scotland goalkeeper Cieran Slicker has debut to forget in home defeat to Iceland|date=6 June 2025|website=Welwyn Hatfield Times}}</ref> On 18 November 2025, he scored a stoppage-time goal in a 4–2 victory over Denmark in the last match of [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group C|Group C]], securing his nation's place in the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]] for the first time since 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/47011300/scotland-vs-denmark-football-live-follow-world-cup-qualifier-winner-takes-all-hampden-park |title=Scotland vs Denmark as it happened: Scotland reach first World Cup in 28 years with 4-2 win |publisher=ESPN |date=18 November 2025 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/kieran-tierney-very-special-scotland-world-cup-b2868202.html|title=Kieran Tierney revels in 'very special' night after firing Scotland to the World Cup|date=19 November 2025|website=The Independent}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Tierney became an ambassador for the [[Scottish Society for Prevention of Cruelty to Animals]] (SSPCA) in June 2021.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/in-your-area/lanarkshire/ex-celtic-star-kieran-tierney-24429176 |title=Ex-Celtic star Kieran Tierney new ambassador for SSPCA |newspaper=Daily Record |first=Leona |last=Greenan |date=30 June 2021 |accessdate=18 October 2022}}</ref>

